“It is another time to prove them wrong by being the top scorer,” said Shirao to Nation Sport, adding that on several occasions, top teams in the country have denied him the opportunity to attend trials due to his physique.
The burly Gogo Boys talisman says that in the local football scene, he looks up to Enock Agwanda who despite being beefy like him, has been banging goals in the top tier.





“He (Agwanda) is the man I look up to because he keeps on scoring in spite of his size. Whenever he scores, I always get the urge to keep on pushing myself to also excel,” he said.
And as the tournament, which has been held annually since 2015 enters the semi-finals round on Thursday at Woodley Grounds in Kibra, it looks Shirao will have to fight tooth and nail to succeed in his mission.
While he is at the helm of the scorers chat on eight goals, he is followed closely by four players who are tied on seven goals.
“I know it is tricky but I believe I will emerge the best,” he says adding that his target is to score 10 goals. In the 2018 and 2019 events, the 21-year-old clinched the golden boot accolade by scoring six and seven goals respectively.
Gogo Boys coach Wilberforce Chirisa tipped him to emerge the top scorer of the tournament and also help the team win their first ever title of the competition.



