“In my team I have five strikers but he (Shirao) is my first choice because he pushes himself so much. He always feels very bad when he misses open chances and he is also a team player. I believe in the remaining stage of the tournament, he will still be of importance to us,” said Chirisa.
Gogo Boys will face-off with Leads United in the second semi-final of the competition on Thursday. Soka Talent will square it out with Upper Karen in the first-semi-finals on Wednesday.
The winners of the tournament, whose aim is to keep youths in Kibira away from crime during the festive season, will receive a cash prize of Sh70,000. The first, second and third runners-up will pocket Sh50,000, Sh30,000 and Sh20 000 respectively.
